'''EUFOR Concordia''' was a [[European Union]] (EU) peacekeeping mission in the [[Republic of Macedonia]], which started on 31 March 2003.<ref>{{Cite web|title = European Union - EEAS (European External Action Service) {{!}} CONCORDIA/FYROM|url = http://www.eeas.europa.eu/csdp/missions-and-operations/concordia/index_en.htm|website = www.eeas.europa.eu|accessdate = 2015-08-18}}</ref> The EU took over from NATO's operation [[Allied Harmony]] and deployed around 300 troops to provide security to EU and [[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]] (OSCE) monitors overseeing the implementation of the [[Ohrid Framework Agreement]]. It  thus became the first ever military operation of the EU.

EUFOR Concordia was a significant event in the evolution of the EU's security cooperation. In the words of the then EU High Representative for the Common Foreign and Security Policy, Javier Solana, when the Common European Foreign and Security Policy started only about a decade before, in 1992, "[f]ew then believed that... we would send out men in arms under the EU's flag."<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.consilium.europa.eu/uedocs/cms_data/docs/pressdata/en/articles/78480.pdf|title = A joint effort for peace and stability|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = Solana|first = Javier}}</ref>

On 15 December 2003 the EUFOR Concordia was replaced by an EU Police Mission, code-named EUPOL PROXIMA, and the 400 EU soldiers were replaced by 200 EU police officers.<ref>{{Cite web|title = European Union - EEAS (European External Action Service) {{!}} EUPOL PROXIMA/FYROM|url = http://www.eeas.europa.eu/csdp/missions-and-operations/proxima-fyrom/index_en.htm|website = www.eeas.europa.eu|accessdate = 2015-08-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title = EU's first military mission ends|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/3321637.stm|newspaper = BBC|date = 2003-12-15|access-date = 2015-08-18}}</ref>

