'''''Les dialoguistes''''' ("The Dialoguers") is the [[French language]] popular term for a faction within the [[Algeria]]n political and military establishment during that country's [[Algerian Civil War|civil war]], which from 1992 pitted [[Islamism|Islamist]] [[Rebellion|rebels]] against a military-installed government. It was mostly used as contrast to ''[[les éradicateurs]]'', the hardline tendency within the security and political elite which saw no room for compromise with Islamist politicians, and believed that militant organizations should be eliminated through force, who were refusing talks with their representatives.

Supported by most of the opposition parties, notably in the 1995 [[Sant'Egidio Platform]], the ''dialoguiste'' faction eventually gained the upper hand, and the [[Abdelaziz Bouteflika|Bouteflika]] presidency (1999-) has been marked by [[amnesty|amnesties]] and attempt to draw Islamists back into constitutional politics.
